Threat Modeling Report

Created on 11/7/2018 8:29:08 PM

Threat Model Name: Mailpile External Data Flows

Owner: Team ASJY

Reviewer:

Contributors: Seth Redwine, Jeffrey Allen, Andrew Hassing, Yuchen Wang

Description: This Level 0 and Level 1 describe Mailpile's data flows when sending or recieving email.

Assumptions: 1. Malware is not present on the local machine.

External Dependencies:

Interaction: Commands

1. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Mailpile may be able to impersonate the context of User in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

2. Elevation by Changing the Execution Flow in Mailpile  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:An attacker may pass data into Mailpile in order to change the flow of program execution within Mailpile to the attacker's choosing.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

3. Mailpile May be Subject to Elevation of Privilege Using Remote Code Execution  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:User may be able to remotely execute code for Mailpile.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

4. Data Flow Input Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

5. Potential Process Crash or Stop for Mailpile  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Mailpile crashes, halts, stops or runs slowly; in all cases violating an availability metric.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

6. Data Flow Sniffing  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Data flowing across Commands may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. Consider encrypting the data flow.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

7. Potential Data Repudiation by Mailpile  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Mailpile claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

8. Potential Lack of Input Validation for Mailpile  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Data flowing across Commands may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to a denial of service attack against Mailpile or an elevation of privilege attack against Mailpile or an information disclosure by Mailpile. Failure to verify that input is as expected is a root cause of a very large number of exploitable issues. Consider all paths and the way they handle data. Verify that all input is verified for correctness using an approved list input validation approach.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

9. Spoofing the Mailpile Process  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Mailpile may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to information disclosure by User. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination process.
Justification:Will be examined in Level 1.

Interaction: Authentication Data

26. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:App may be able to impersonate the context of UI in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:App already has higher privelege than UI.

27. UI Process Memory Tampered  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:If UI is given access to memory, such as shared memory or pointers, or is given the ability to control what App executes (for example, passing back a function pointer.), then UI can tamper with App. Consider if the function could work with less access to memory, such as passing data rather than pointers. Copy in data provided, and then validate it.
Justification:UI doesn&#39;t have access to memory.

28. Spoofing the UI Process  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:UI may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to App. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the source process.
Justification:User is authenticated before allowing commands to be executed.

29. Spoofing the App Process  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:App may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to information disclosure by UI. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination process.
Justification:UI doesn&#39;t have access to any data.

30. Potential Lack of Input Validation for App  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Data flowing across Authentication Data may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to a denial of service attack against App or an elevation of privilege attack against App or an information disclosure by App. Failure to verify that input is as expected is a root cause of a very large number of exploitable issues. Consider all paths and the way they handle data. Verify that all input is verified for correctness using an approved list input validation approach.
Justification:Data is verified in App.

31. Potential Data Repudiation by App  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:App claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:If App doesn&#39;t recieve this Authentication data, it doesn&#39;t matter.

32. Data Flow Sniffing  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Data flowing across Authentication Data may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. Consider encrypting the data flow.
Justification:This communication happens on the local machine, where it&#39;s not as vulnerable to sniffing.
